properties.name: Ogden Street
properties.description: Named for Anthony Ogden, mayor (1924-1926) and MLA for Townsville in the early 20<sup>th</sup> century (Mathew, 2008, 95).
properties.refs: Mathew, J. (2008). Highways and Byways: The Origin of Townsville Street Names (Revised ed.). Townsville, QLD: Townsville Library Service.

properties.name: Hanran Street
properties.description: Named for Patrick Francis Hanran, mayor from 1870 onwards for multiple terms. He was also a general merchant in Townsville. (Mathew, 2008, p. 58-59).
properties.refs: Mathew, J. (2008). Highways and Byways: The Origin of Townsville Street Names (Revised ed.). Townsville, QLD: Townsville Library Service.

properties.name: Thorpe Street
properties.description: "Named after Thomas Edward Thorpe, sharebroker and Alderman" (Mathew, 2008, p. 118).
properties.refs: Mathew, J. (2008). Highways and Byways: The Origin of Townsville Street Names (Revised ed.). Townsville, QLD: Townsville Library Service.

properties.name: Herbert Street
properties.description: "Named after Sir Robert George Wyndham Herbert, secretary to Sir George Bowen (first governor of QLD) and Colonial Secretary for just over six years from December 1859 - February 1866 (Mathew, 2008, p. 62).
properties.refs: Mathew, J. (2008). Highways and Byways: The Origin of Townsville Street Names (Revised ed.). Townsville, QLD: Townsville Library Service.

properties.name: Knapp Street
properties.description: Named for Henry Knapp, a solicitor who held various political positions during the latter half of the 19<sup>th</sup>century who left office permanently after being sued for larceny (his legal licence was also suspended later). (Mathew, 2008, p. 73).
properties.refs: Mathew, J. (2008). Highways and Byways: The Origin of Townsville Street Names (Revised ed.). Townsville, QLD: Townsville Library Service.

properties.name: Isley Street
properties.description: Named for John Bacey Isley, a Queensland Native Mounted Police Inspector in the late 19<sup>th</sup> century (Mathew, 2008, p. 67).
properties.refs: Mathew, J. (2008). Highways and Byways: The Origin of Townsville Street Names (Revised ed.). Townsville, QLD: Townsville Library Service.

properties.name: Bundock Street
properties.description: Named for Arthur Glennie Bundock, who served in a variety of public service roles including Alderman and Mayor in the late 19<sup>th</sup> century (Mathew, 2008, p. 24).
properties.refs: Mathew, J. (2008). Highways and Byways: The Origin of Townsville Street Names (Revised ed.). Townsville, QLD: Townsville Library Service.

properties.description: Named for Archibald Archer, member of the Legislative Assembly in the late 19<sup>th</sup> century. He later, "served in the McIlwraith Ministry as Colonial Treasurer and Secretary for Public Instruction in 1882-83" (Mathew, 2008, p. 10).
properties.refs: Mathew, J. (2008). Highways and Byways: The Origin of Townsville Street Names (Revised ed.). Townsville, QLD: Townsville Library Service.

properties.name: Ross Street
properties.description: Named for William Alfred Ross, hotel operator and "elected a member of the first Townsville Council in the following year. He was Mayor in 1868." (Mathew, 2008, p. 109).
properties.refs: Mathew, J. (2008). Highways and Byways: The Origin of Townsville Street Names (Revised ed.). Townsville, QLD: Townsville Library Service.

properties.name: Griffith Street
properties.description: Named for Sir Samuel Griffith, a premier of Queensland. "At the first Federal Convention held in Sydney during March 1891," Mathew (2008) notes, "he was largely responsible for the draft constitution which was adopted." (p. 56).
properties.refs: Mathew, J. (2008). Highways and Byways: The Origin of Townsville Street Names (Revised ed.). Townsville, QLD: Townsville Library Service.

properties.name: Barlow Street
properties.description: Named for Andrew Henry Barlow, a member of the Legislative Assembly in the late 19<sup>th</sup> century. As Mathew (2008) argues, "Barlow opposed Chinese immigration, supported the Eight-Hour Bill but favoured plural voting because he believed that unrestrained democracy fostered despotism" (p. 15).
properties.refs: Mathew, J. (2008). Highways and Byways: The Origin of Townsville Street Names (Revised ed.). Townsville, QLD: Townsville Library Service.

properties.name: Morehead Street
properties.description: Named for Boyd Dunlop Morehead, a businessperson and politician (Mathew, 2008, p. 15). He became Premier of Queensland later in life from 1888 - 1890, resigning as he "felt unable to continue with such diminished support" after imposing unfavourable tax measures (p. 42)
properties.refs:
Fitzgerald, R., Megarrity, L., & Symons, D. (2009). Made in Queensland: A New History. St Lucia, QLD: University of Queensland Press.
Mathew, J. (2008). Highways and Byways: The Origin of Townsville Street Names (Revised ed.). Townsville, QLD: Townsville Library Service.

properties.name: Benwell Road
properties.description: Named for Hugh Percy Hamilton Benwell (1852-1901), "the first secretary of the Townsville Chamber of Commerce when it was formed in 1882 and in the same year was appointed surveyor and valuator to the Thuringowa Divisional Board at a salary of seventy-five pounds per annum" (Mathew, 2008, p. 18).
properties.refs: Mathew, J. (2008). Highways and Byways: The Origin of Townsville Street Names (Revised ed.). Townsville, QLD: Townsville Library Service.

properties.name: Macrossan Road
properties.description: Named for John Murtagh Macrossan (1833-1891), politician. "In 1886" Mathew (2008) argues, "he came out openly for complete separation for the North and in parliament made one of Australia’s great statements for local self-government" (p. 81).
properties.refs: Mathew, J. (2008). Highways and Byways: The Origin of Townsville Street Names (Revised ed.). Townsville, QLD: Townsville Library Service.

properties.refs: Mathew, J. (2008). Highways and Byways: The Origin of Townsville Street Names (Revised ed.). Townsville, QLD: Townsville Library Service.

properties.name: Nelson Street
properties.description: Named for Sir Hugh Muir Nelson (1833-1906), politician. "His handling of the Queensland National Bank crisis" Mathew (2008) argues, "was his greatest and shrewdest service to colonial bourgeois society. When the Queensland National Bank suspended payment on 15th May 189? he declared it basically sound, although aware of its true state. The government then rescued the bank at its own and depositors’ expense." (p. 92).
properties.refs: Mathew, J. (2008). Highways and Byways: The Origin of Townsville Street Names (Revised ed.). Townsville, QLD: Townsville Library Service.

properties.name: Boundary Street
properties.description: Named for the fact that it served as the boundary between South Townsville and Railway Estate (Mathew, 2008, p. 21). In Townsville, as in other Australian communities such as Brisbane, Boundary Street also marked the line across which Indigenous peoples were not allowed to cross.
properties.refs: Mathew, J. (2008). Highways and Byways: The Origin of Townsville Street Names (Revised ed.). Townsville, QLD: Townsville Library Service.
